\begin_layout Standard
We developed an ICKMR study design,
 with walrus as a case study,
 as an example for other researchers embarking on this evolving type of study.
 We investigated whether using CKMR could improve expected precision in estimates of adult female walrus population size.
 To do this,
 we developed a CKMR model with individual recaptures as a kin type,
 in addition to parent-offspring and half-sibling pairs.
 We made simplifying assumptions for tractability.
 For example,
 we decided to exclude paternal kinships and not to model males at all,
 since there would be minimal useful information in the data and extra complications in the modelling;
 and we opted for a stage-structured (rather than age-structured) model,
 assuming unselective sampling by age within stage (which may not be particularly accurate for juveniles).
 In future,
 it may be worthwhile to develop a fully age-structured version of the model,
 which would simplify the kinship probabilities for the self-recapture data.
 We further assumed quasi-equilibrium population dynamics across the period 2000â€“2028,
 with a constant rate of population change and stable age composition.
 This is a simplification during at least part of the time frame (Taylor et al.
 2018).
 Nevertheless,
 given that our general purpose was to investigate sample size requirements,
 we believe our simplifications were reasonable.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The walrus project was initially planned as an IMR project with five years of total survey effort between 2013 and 2017 and another five years planned between 2023 and 2027.
 Since the 2023 survey went ahead,
 we considered that year as fixed in our design scenarios.
 We found that expected CVs on adult female abundance were substantially (>30%) and consistently lower when using ICKMR than when using IMR.
 Our results indicated that by adding CKMR,
 a CV of 0.1 on estimates of adult female population size (with planned sample sizes per year of 1600) could be achieved with 1.75 years of total future (post-2017) survey effort (i.e.
 2800 new samples) whereas IMR alone would require
