.
 We expect to include ageing error in our ICKMR model when data are available,
 but we opted not to include it in our design calculations (i.e.,
 we assumed that there is no error),
 because we do not yet know how large the errors will be.
 Design calculations can be re-run easily enough when better estimates of ageing error are available.
 For that purpose,
 it would also be preferable to move to a fully-age-structured model,
 rather than stage-structured.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
CKMR is a major advance in population ecology,
 and this paper provides a significant step towards fully leveraging this new method.
 We demonstrate how CKMR can be combined with IMR into a unified model and lead to substantially improved precision in estimates of population size and demographic parameters compared to IMR alone.
 We provide an example of ICKMR study design,
 including model development,
 model checking,
 and design calculations,
 and show how simulated data can be used to evaluate different proposed survey designs.
 While we used walrus as a motivating example,
 we expect that ICKMR will be a useful tool for estimating population parameters of interest across a range of taxa.
\end_layout

